Growing on a partially submerged decorticated conifer log at the edge of a pond near Abies balsamea, Tsuga canadensis and Pinus strobus. Cheilocystidia abundant and similar to the pleurocystidia. results.notes:
Found growing in grass next to gazebo in my backyard. No dung or decaying material visible to me.
Description: Small (but not at all tiny), smooth, yellowish-brown mushroom with conical cap, but no distinct knob. Does not bruise blue. Bruising not observed, but some brown areas present on stalk (possibly dirt?).
Cap: Not yet measured, but looks to be ranging from 1-1.5" in diameter. Conical with no distinct knob. Not sticky or slimy at all. Feels like a typical mushroom to the touch. Darker closer to the top of the mushroom, fading to off-white around the edges. No KOH present to test.
Odor: Strong earthy smell. Otherwise no notable odor. Did not taste test.
Gills: Attached, close, purplish-brown when fresh. Darker brown when not. Does not excrete when sliced.
Stalk: ~1-2.5" tall. Not frail, but not notably strong. white near the top of the stalk, but brown underneath (likely dirt). Ring present with close observation.
Spores: No microscope available. Spore print black.
Other Notes: Found growing in grass next to gazebo in backyard. 2 (maybe 3, unsure if the same) of the same species growing nearby each other but detached from one another. A different species of mushrooms nearby, also growing in threes. A third species of fungi growing nearby, but stalkless.

results.notes:
Same day, location, and habitat as obs 520287.
The spores appear to have darkened in Melzers (compared to 520287). But, when compared to my photos of clearly dextrinoid Galerina spores, these are not as dark or purple (in Melzers).
Spores 9-10 × 5.5-7.
Cheilocystidia numerous, variably-shaped.
Caulocystidia not found.
The only source I have found that mentions the covering of fibrils on the cap is Baroni (Mushrooms of NE USA and E CA). His photo also shows this trait. Baroni suggests that the fibrils disappear upon expansion of the caps. However, the caps seen in this observation appear to be mature. I think it’s possible the eroding of the fibrils may be induced (or at least enhanced) by rainfall. The specimens seen here were found after a two week period of almost no rainfall (~1 mm during one event).
Spores of this collection (and several other similar collections) mounted in Melzers variably darkened… some almost no darkening (ochre to light brown), some becoming darker brown, and some appearing to qualify as dextrinoid (dark purplish-brown).
